message: Ensure exceptions from methodBlock() don't result in unrooted tests. <enter>  <enter> The introduction of the runLeaf() method in BlockJUnit4ClassRunner in <enter> JUnit 4.9 introduced a regression with regard to exception handling. <enter>  <enter> Specifically, the invocation of methodBlock() is no longer executed <enter> within a try-catch block as was the case in previous versions of JUnit. <enter>  <enter> Custom modifications to methodBlock() or the methods it invokes may in <enter> fact throw exceptions. In such cases, exceptions thrown from <enter> methodBlock() cause the current test execution to abort immediately. As <enter> a result, the failing test method is unrooted in test reports, and <enter> subsequent test methods are never invoked. Furthermore, RunListeners <enter> registered with JUnit are not notified. <enter>  <enter> This commit addresses this issue by wrapping the invocation of <enter> methodBlock() within a try-catch block. If an exception is not thrown, <enter> the resulting Statement is passed to runLeaf(). If an exception is <enter> thrown, it is wrapped in a Fail statement which is passed to runLeaf(). <enter>  <enter> Closes #1066 <enter> Closes #1082
new_message1: Ensure exceptions from <iden>() don't result in unrooted tests.  <enter> The introduction of the <iden>() method in  <file_name>  in <iden> <version> introduced a regression with regard to exception handling. <enter> Specifically, the invocation of <iden>() is no longer executed within a try-catch block as was the case in previous versions of <iden>. <enter> <iden> modifications to <iden>() or the methods it invokes may in fact throw exceptions. In such cases, exceptions thrown from <iden>() cause the current test execution to abort immediately. As a result, the failing test method is unrooted in test reports, and subsequent test methods are never invoked. Furthermore, RunListeners registered with <iden> are not notified. <enter> This commit addresses this issue by wrapping the invocation of <iden>() within a try-catch block. If an exception is not thrown, the resulting <iden> is passed to <iden>(). In both cases EPL would have <enter> been fine. <enter> * Netbeans can't ship JUnit [4] <enter> * OpenJDK uses TestNG instead of JUnit [5] <enter>  <enter> Mike Milinkovich from the Eclipse Foundation wrote [1] <enter>  <enter> > Back in 2009, the CPL was superseded by the EPL. This means that the <enter> > EPL is the successor version of the CPL. It also means that using the <enter> > CPL is the licensing equivalent of using deprecated code. <enter> > <enter> > Because the EPL is the successor version to the CPL, the 'new version <enter> > re-licensing' clause in Section 7 of the CPL applies. In other words, <enter> > you can re-license your project without seeking the approval of all <enter> > of your contributors. <enter> > The CPL and EPL basically differ by about one sentence, which you can <enter> > see here. The difference relates to the scope of patent licenses <enter> > terminated should someone sue another party for patent infringement. <enter> > This is the kind of stuff that lawyers love, but most developers <enter> > don't really care about. <enter>  <enter> On the migration from CPL to EPL Mike Milinkovich wrote [2] <enter>  <enter> > There was a two step process that was followed to make this happen. <enter> > First, following the terms of the CPL, IBM assigned the <enter> > responsibility to serve as the Agreement Steward of the CPL to the <enter> > Eclipse Foundation. Second, the Eclipse Foundation officially <enter> > recognized the EPL 1.0 as the new version of the CPL 1.0. In OSI <enter> > license terminology, the EPL now supersedes the CPL. <enter> > <enter> > A quick read of the two licenses will quickly show that they are very <enter> > very close. Other than their names and (previously) their Agreement <enter> > Stewards, the only substantive difference is the breadth of the <enter> > patent license termination in the event of a patent law suit. (See <enter> > the second paragraph of Section 7.) For more information on the <enter> > relationship between the CPL and the EPL see the EPL FAQ. <enter>  <enter> You can find more information about the difference at [3]. <enter>  <enter> The new `LICENSE.txt` is based on a plain text version of the EPL with <enter> formatted so that the diff is a clean as possible. <enter>  <enter> I'll submit another pull request for the gh-pages branch. <enter>  <enter>  [1] http://mmilinkov.wordpress.com/2013/02/13/jruby-moves-to-the-epl/ <enter>  [2] http://mmilinkov.wordpress.com/2009/04/16/one-small-step-towards-reducing-license-proliferation/ <enter>  [3] http://www.eclipse.org/legal/eplfaq.php#EPLDIFFER <enter>  [4] https://netbeans.org/community/releases/70/relnotes.html#deprecated <enter>  [5] http://openjdk.java.net/jtreg/build.html

message: Bug: ParentRunner lost test Class from a separate class loader (#1252) <enter>  <enter> * Bug: ParentRunner lost test Class from a separate class loader <enter>  <enter> When junit.jar located in one ClassLoader but runing tests in another ParentRunner can lost information about run class. <enter> For example if use @ClassRule and request test class(org.junit.runner.Description#getTestClass) we can get null, <enter> because ParentRunner instead of set Class as is to Description tranform it to class name string, <enter> as result org.junit.runner.Description#getTestClass execute Class.forName and can't find test class. <enter>  <enter> Spring-test fail with exception if we try use SpringClassRule <enter>  <enter> ``` <enter> java.lang.NullPointerException <enter>  at org.springframework.test.context.junit4.rules.SpringClassRule.validateSpringMethodRuleConfiguration(SpringClassRule.java:186) <enter>  at org.springframework.test.context.junit4.rules.SpringClassRule.apply(SpringClassRule.java:134) <enter>  at org.junit.rules.RunRules.applyAll(RunRules.java:26) <enter>  at org.junit.rules.RunRules.<init>(RunRules.java:15) <enter>  at org.junit.runners.ParentRunner.withClassRules(ParentRunner.java:245) <enter>  at org.junit.runners.ParentRunner.classBlock(ParentRunner.java:194) <enter>  at org.junit.runners.ParentRunner.run(ParentRunner.java:362) <enter>  at org.junit.runner.JUnitCore.run(JUnitCore.java:137) <enter> ``` <enter>  <enter> As solution, now ParentRunner create Descriptor with explicit specify Class, name and uses annotations. <enter>  <enter> * Restore backward compatibility with sub class of ParentRunner that override getName method <enter> * Add ParentRunnerClassLoaderTest to AllClassesTests suite
new_message1: Bug:  <file_name>  lost test <iden> from a separate class loader ( <link> )  <enter> * Bug:  <file_name>  lost test <iden> from a separate class loader <enter> When junit.jar located in one <iden> but runing tests in another  <file_name>  can lost information about run class. For example if use <iden> and request test  <method_name>  <file_name>  we can get null, because  <file_name>  instead of set <iden> as is to  <file_name>  tranform it to class name string, as result  <method_name>  execute <iden>.forName and can't find test class. <enter> Spring-test fail with exception if we try use SpringClassRule <enter>  <enter> As solution, now  <file_name>  create Descriptor with explicit specify <iden>, name and uses annotations. <enter> * Restore backward compatibility with sub class of  <file_name>  that override <iden> method * Add  <file_name>  to  <file_name>  suite

Non-200 responses delivered to the body observer would be forwarded to onError. If that callback threw a fatal exception, it would be re-delivered to the body observer despite it having already called a downstream terminal method. The fatal error should have been propagated by the async observer instead of attempting to make its way back downstream.

message: Clarify the role of spring-boot-starter-cache <enter>  <enter> The cache abstraction is a core feature of the Spring Framework. Spring <enter> Boot provides that artifact via the `spring-boot-starter-cache` starter. <enter>  <enter> It is quite easy to 'only' add the cache library dependencies and forget <enter> about this extra dependencies since `@EnableCaching` is available by <enter> default. This commit clarifies the role of the starer in each section so <enter> that it is more obvious. We're already explaining this at the beginning <enter> of the section but it seems that's not enough. <enter>  <enter> Closes gh-7071

If they all match, the inner <enter> class will be reported as a positive match in the auto-configuration <enter> report even if the outer class does not match as a result of the <enter> subsequent evaluation of a REGISTER_BEAN condition. <enter>  <enter> Fixes gh-2122

message: A Pipe. <enter>  <enter> This is something we need to implement HttpURLConnection atop the native <enter> OkHttp API. The application thread wants to be active, writing to its <enter> OutputStream. But in OkHttp's API, this work wants to happen in the <enter> RequestBody.writeTo() callback. To make this work we give the HttpUrlConnection <enter> OutputStream the sink end of the pipe, and the RequestBody the source end <enter> of the pipe. It's a bit of plumbing, but the benefit is that backpressure, <enter> timeouts, and failures will propagate as expected.

To make this work we give the HttpUrlConnection OutputStream the sink end of the pipe, and the RequestBody the source end of the pipe. message: OkBuffer API sketch. <enter>  <enter> I'm unhappy with java.io: <enter>  * No timeouts. <enter>  * Every layer needs to copy bytes around. Always copying bytes. <enter>  * Features like mark/reset and available() are clumsy. <enter>  * Its awkard in mixed text/binary protocols like HTTP because <enter>    character decoding is separate and takes over the stream. <enter>  <enter> Unfortunately java.nio isn't better, just different: <enter>  * It's complex. <enter>  * Buffers are fixed size. <enter>  * No built-in buffer pooling. <enter>  * Features like mark/reset/position are clumsy. <enter>  <enter> This is an obnoxious attempt at a 3rd I/O interface, mostly <enter> inspired by InputStream and OutputStream, but using growable <enter> buffers instead of byte arrays as the core data container.
new_message1: <file_name>  API sketch.  <enter> <iden>'m unhappy with java.io:  * No timeouts.  * Every layer needs to copy bytes around. Always copying bytes.  * Features like mark/reset and available() are clumsy.  * Its awkard in mixed text/binary protocols like <iden> because  character decoding is separate and takes over the stream. <enter> Unfortunately java.nio isn't better, just different:  * It's complex.  * <iden> are fixed size.  * No built-in buffer pooling.  * Features like mark/reset/position are clumsy. <enter> This is an obnoxious attempt at a 3rd <iden>/O interface, mostly inspired by <iden> and <iden>, but using growable buffers instead of byte arrays as the core data container.

message: Only use a property where multiple entries need syncing <enter>  <enter> * The hamcrest version is only used in one place, i.e. the dependency. <enter> * Using properties to define dependency versions can cause issues for others. <enter> * Using properties to define a shared version across multiple dependencies causes less issues <enter>   when you have multiple dependencies that need to be kept in sync. <enter> * We only have one dependency here and it doesn't need syncing to any other dependency <enter> * Therefore the right thing is to just specify the version in the dependency <enter> * End users can still override the dependency in their poms.
new_message1: Only use a property where multiple entries need syncing  <enter> * The hamcrest version is only used in one place, i.e. the dependency. * Using properties to define dependency versions can cause issues for others. * Using properties to define a shared version across multiple dependencies causes less issues when you have multiple dependencies that need to be kept in sync. * We only have one dependency here and it doesn't need syncing to any other dependency * Therefore the right thing is to just specify the version in the dependency * End users can still override the dependency in their poms.

It faithfully kept the behavior <enter> from PR #1257. <enter>  <enter> The modification of the timeout behavior during *connection* <enter> caused problems on Android. Now that the two types of error <enter> handling are split it's possible to deal with them <enter> differently and return the connection behavior to trying <enter> the next route. Often the <enter> exception is thrown during a subsequent test. <enter>  <enter> This change logs the exception but prevent it from <enter> propagating out of the top of the call stack. This decreases <enter> overall flakiness.

message: Fail HTTP/2 connections if the pong is not received. (#3878) <enter>  <enter> This removes the Ping abstraction from our http2 package. This was written as <enter> if it were a public API, but never exposed to any callers but tests. Removing <enter> it makes it easier to lock down how pings are used. <enter>  <enter> This also removes the NullServer class, replacing it with a new SocketPolicy <enter> on MockWebServer. The new SocketPolicy, STALL_SOCKET_AT_START, allows us to <enter> do TLS and negotiate an HTTP/2 connection without actually building a proper <enter> Http2Connection and without responding to pings. <enter>  <enter> The behavior in HTTP/2 connections is modeled after our behavior in web sockets. <enter> We count outgoing pings, incoming pongs, and confirm that the pongs are keeping <enter> up. If later we make this policy more sophisticated we can track the changes <enter> in both places. <enter>  <enter> Closes: https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/3261

We <enter> don't yet fail the connection if pongs are not received. <enter>  <enter> For follow-up there's some work to remove exising APIs to send pings <enter> through the HTTP/2 APIs. These are unused and make it awkard to <enter> confirm that only the automatic pings are being replied to. <enter>  <enter> See https://github.com/square/okhttp/issues/3261

message: Register an AuthenticationManager in security autoconfig <enter>  <enter> This is quite a big step, but I think it helps a lot. Since Spring <enter> Boot always creates an AuthenticationManager if it doesn't find one <enter> already registered, it makes sense to also make it into a @Bean. <enter> Spring Security does not register its AuthenticationManager by <enter> default though, so we have to do that for it if the user has created <enter> one with an @Autowired AuthenticationManagerBuilder, but not registered <enter> it as a @Bean. <enter>  <enter> Having the @Bean (marked @Primary to prevent issues with @Autowired) <enter> makes it easier to reason about what Spring Boot has done for you, and <enter> easier to default in simple use cases to the boot-created <enter> AuthenticationManager. For example, if I want an OAuth2 Authorization <enter> Server with password grant, it makes total sense for the <enter> AuthenticationManager for users to be the same as the @Primary one. <enter> Now it is easy to set that up (just @Autowire it).

message: Use Google's Maven Central mirror <enter>  <enter> We are using Maven 3.1.1 which by default uses HTTP instead of HTTPS for <enter> resolving artifacts from Maven Central. By using an HTTPS mirror of Maven Central the build on Travis <enter> will work again. <enter>  <enter> I chose Google's mirror because Travis uses this mirror by default, too. <enter> I did not upgrade to a new version of Maven because there is no newer <enter> version with Java 5 support and it should be possible to build JUnit 4 <enter> with Java 5 so that we can easily ensure that it works with Java 5.
